handist.collections

Class RangedList<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • handist.collections.RangedList<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - type handled by the collection
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Chunk, LazyRangedList, RangedListView

    public abstract class RangedList<T>
extends Object
implements Iterable<T>
    Abstract class describing a list defined on long indices. Entries can be defined on any index contained within the LongRange used to initialize the collection.

      • forEach

        public final <U> void forEach(BiConsumer<? super T,Consumer<? super U>> action,
                              Consumer<? super U> receiver)
        Performs the provided action on each element contained by this instance, and potentially collect/extract some information into the provided receiver.

        The BiConsumer is applied on each element contained in the collection (first parameter of the BiConsumer) with the receiver provided as second parameter of this method as the second parameter of the BiConsumer. This allows you to make modifications to individual elements and potentially extract some information (of type U) and store it in the receiver provided as second parameter.

        If you do not need to extract any information from the elements contained in this instance, you should use forEach(Consumer) instead.

        Type Parameters:
        U - type of the collected instances
        Parameters:
        action - action to perform on each element, potentially
        receiver - collector of information extracted

                              BiConsumer<? super T,Consumer<? super U>> action,

        Performs the provided action on elements contained by this instance, and potentially collect/extract some information into the provided receiver. This method has the same effect as forEach(BiConsumer, Consumer) but its application is restricted to the range specified as first parameter.

        The BiConsumer is applied on each element contained in the collection (first parameter of the BiConsumer) with the receiver provided as second parameter of this method as the second parameter of the BiConsumer. This allows you to make modifications to individual elements and potentially extract some information (of type U) and store it in the receiver provided as second parameter.

        If you do not need to extract any information from the elements contained in this instance, you should use forEach(LongRange, Consumer) instead.

        Type Parameters:
        U - type of the collected instances
        Parameters:
        range - range on which the action is to be applied
        action - action to perform on each element, potentially
        receiver - collector of information extracted

      • splitRange

        public LinkedList<RangedList<T>> splitRange(long... splitPoints)
        Separates this instance into multiple RangedLists using the points given as parameter.

        For instance, if this instance is defined on a range [a,b) and points l, m, and n are given as parameter, this method will return 4 RangedList defined on [a,l), [l,m), [m,n), and [n,b).

        The user will be careful to sort the points given as parameter in ascending order. Exceptions during the creation of RangedList will be thrown otherwise.

        Parameters:
        splitPoints - the points at which this instance needs to be cut
        Returns:
        this instance entries split into several RangedList

      • subList

        public RangedList<T> subList(long begin,
                             long end)
        Provides a RangedList of the elements contained in this instance from index begin to index end.

        If the provided range exceeds the indices contained in this instance (i.e. if begin is lower than the lowest index contained in this instance, or if end is higher than the highest index contained in this instance) the method will return the elements it contains that fit within the provided range.

        Parameters:
        begin - starting index of the desired sub-list
        end - last index of the desired sub-list (exlusive)
        Returns:
        a ranged list of the elements contained in this RangedList that fit in the provided range.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if begin is superior to end.
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the provided range has no intersection with the range of this instance.

      • subList

        public RangedList<T> subList(LongRange range)
        Provides a RangedList of the elements contained in this instance on the specified LongRange.

        If the provided range exceeds the indices contained in this instance (i.e. if lower bound of the LongRange is lower than the lowest index contained in this instance, or if the upper bound of the provided LongRange is higher than the highest index contained in this instance) the method will return the elements it contains that fit within the provided range.

        Parameters:
        range - range of indices of which a copy is desired
        Returns:
        a ranged list of the elements contained in this RangedList that fit in the provided range.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if begin is superior to end.
